article.description: Penny Taylor emerged from a shooting slump to score 24 points and lead the Cleveland Rockers to a 73-50 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs.
article.headline: Taylor: 24 points, 11 rebounds, five assists
article.linkText: Penny from heaven: Taylor scores 24 in Rockers' win
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Penny Taylor was eager to get her game back after two dismal performances and did so with a flourish Thursday night.

Taylor emerged from a shooting slump to score 24 points and lead the Cleveland Rockers to a 73-50 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs.

"I really wanted to be aggressive and look for my shot,'' Taylor said. "It was about regaining confidence and going out to help my team from the opening tip.''

Taylor, who had totaled just eight points in two previous games, hit her first three shots, including two 3-pointers. The second-year guard also had career highs of 11 rebounds and five assists.

"When Penny is playing well, she takes something that looks like it is going to be bad and turns it into something good,'' Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. "She reacts so well. When she is quick to loose balls, everything else follows for her.''

Taylor averaged 16.2 points over her first 10 games before
shooting a combined 4-for-16 in two games earlier this week after
missing some practice time with back spasms.

"That's an excuse I don't want to use, but I do think my mental approach needed to change,'' Taylor said. "It was like I had to get past the thoughts in the back of my mind. Mentally, I said just forget about my back because I knew I was fine. Then everything went well.''

Taylor shot 8-for-15 from the field against the Monarchs (2-10),
who lost their third in a row and dropped to 0-6 on the road.

Chasity Melvin added 18 points and 12 rebounds for Cleveland
(5-6), but was most proud of her fifth career 3-pointer.

"I get one a year for my mom,'' said the 6-foot-3 forward-center. "She's going to be telling everybody at work about it tomorrow.''

Tangela Smith led Sacramento with 18 points, and Ruthie Bolton
scored 11, all in the first half, for the Monarchs.

"We took bad shots and gave up points, not a good
combination,'' Monarchs coach Maura McHugh said. "Tangela played
great, but we need people to go in and rebound and give her some
help.''

Cleveland's front line of Taylor, Melvin and center Ann Wauters
simply dominated, combining for 50 points and 31 rebounds.
Cleveland held a 44-27 rebounding advantage.

"Defense and rebounding go hand-in-hand,'' Hughes said. "What we do defensively builds the foundation and Chasity really made some plays on the glass.''

Sacramento again played without injured point guard Ticha Penicheiro and forward Yolanda Griffith. Penicheiro has a strained right shoulder, while Griffith has a bulging disc in her neck.

Andrea Nagy, starting in place of perennial WNBA assists leader
Penicheiro, had 11 assists.

"Andrea played well, but we really do miss Ticha and Yolanda,''
McHugh said. We really have to pick up the slack by committee.''

Taylor had 11 points in the first half to help Cleveland lead at
the break 31-25.

The Rockers made seven of their first 11 shots to open a 16-4 lead.

   Then Bolton sparked the Monarchs, who got as close as 18-16
before Melvin scored five points and Taylor three in a 13-5 spurt
that put the Rockers back in command.
